ngs":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Morton   1.","Spanish (<b>Moretón</b>): nickname from <i>moretón</i> ‘brown, tanned’ (of skin).","French: nickname from a double diminutive of   More   2 ‘Moor’. Compare   Moret  ."]},{"name":"Murton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places in northern England, all named in Old English as ‘settlement or enclosure at the marsh or moor’, from <i>mōr</i> ‘marsh, fen, moor’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. There has been considerable confusion with both   Morton   and   Merton  ."]},{"name":"Morten","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortagne in La Manche, France. This surname has probably been confused with   Morton  ."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ann Morton was born in 1420, in Kendal, Westmorland, England, her father, Sir Robert Morton IV, was 20 and her mother, Ales Alice Bozon, was 8. She married Knight de la Beche Richard Beswicke on 3 July 1787, in Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1420–":"1420–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1431–Female":"1431–Surnud","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1439–Male":"1439–Surnud",